Asia
---
Sri Lanka
- National. 3 Jan 2018. In 2017, Sri Lanka saw a record number of dengue fever cases with a total of 184 442, a total more than 3 times higher than in 2016. More than 320 deaths were also reported. The dengue peak was observed during the summer months with more than 41 000 cases reported during July alone. Colombo RDHS [Regional Directorate of Health Services] and Gampaha RDHS saw the most cases, with 34 173 and 31 459, respectively. To put the 2017 epidemic in perspective, there were 55 000 cases reported in 2016 and about 30 000 cases seen in 2015. While dengue was reported from all over the island, approximately 41.53 percent of cases were reported from the Western province. All 4 serotypes of dengue have been seen in Sri Lanka. The current outbreak is predominantly due to serotype 2 (DEN-2), which is not the usual type circulating in Sri Lanka.
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/sri-lanka-dengue-fever-epidemic-2017/

[Maps of Sri Lanka: http://geology.com/world/sri-lanka-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,144]

India
- Maharashtra (Pune). 4 Jan 2018. 15 suspected cases of dengue reported in Pune in 3 days. The number is expected to reduce with decrease in temperature. In 2017 1691 confirmed cases were reported. According to officials, over 41 489 dengue sites were found and treated with insecticides by the department as a measure to prevent the growing number of dengue patients in the city since the outbreak in June [2017].
http://www.hindustantimes.com/pune-news/15-suspected-cases-of-dengue-reported-in-pune-in-3-days/story-vzIsiWerEd1TRgzs53NKHN.html

- New Delhi. 22 Jan 2018. At least 3 people have already been diagnosed with dengue in Delhi. These are the 1st reported cases this year [2018].

Cases of vector-borne diseases are usually reported between mid-July and November-end, but this period may stretch up to mid-December. "3 cases of dengue have been reported till [20 Jan 2018]. However, no cases of malaria or chikungunya have been reported," according to a municipal report released today [22 Jan 2018]. There was no case of any vector-borne disease till [13 Jan 2018].
https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/dengue-strikes-early-in-delhi-with-3-cases-reported-in-january-1803252

[Maps of India: http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,142]

Pakistan
- Sindh (Karachi). 15 Jan 2018. As many as 24 more dengue fever cases were reported throughout Karachi last week [week of 8 Jan 2018], taking the number of reported cases to 47 in the city since 1 Jan 2018. As per the weekly report issued by the Prevention and Control Program for Dengue in Sindh, at least 24 new dengue fever cases surfaced across the city [during 8-15 Jan 2018]. A total of 48 cases have been reported throughout Sindh province, out of which 47 were in Karachi and one from the rest of the province.

In 2017, a total of 2927 dengue cases were reported across Sindh province, out of which 12 died from this fever.

[Maps of Pakistan: http://pakistanmap.facts.co/pakistanmapof/PakistanAdministrativeMap.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,140]

- Maldives. 17 Jan 2018. Health Protection Agency (HPA) has confirmed the number of dengue fever cases reported is comparatively more than the total number of cases reported during the same period of 2017. The 1st portion of each year is active with dengue fever cases reported throughout Maldives. To counter this and raise awareness and promote safety, HPA had initiated special camps last week[week of 8 Jan 2018]. Maldives has reported little over 2000 cases of dengue fever patients in the past 2 years.
https://avas.mv/en/43135

[Maps of the Maldives: http://www.globalcitymap.com/asia/images/maldives-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,143]

- Russia ex Egypt (Hurghada, Red Sea). 19 Jan 2018. In 2017, 2 cases of dengue fever were imported from Hurghada, Egypt, where dengue fever was not considered endemic, to Moscow. These cases show how emergence of dengue fever in popular resort regions on the coast of the Red Sea can spread infection to countries where it is not endemic.
https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/24/4/17-2131_article [ahead of print]

- Thailand. 21 Jan 2018. Chulalongkorn University says that 80 percent of dengue patients don't show symptoms, making the disease more dangerous and sometimes fatal. Teerapong Tantawichien, MD, Professor of Medicine of the Faculty of Medicine, Chulalongkorn University said there are no fewer than 100 000 cases of dengue fever reported every year in Thailand and 70-80 percent of those cases did not exhibit symptoms which can include high fever, rashes, and muscle and joint pain, headache, fatigue, nausea, and vomiting. A dengue vaccine is 65 percent effective among those who have contracted the disease before, he said, adding that 80 percent of vaccinated persons can avoid hospital admission and up to 93 percent don't experience severe symptoms. He cautioned however that those who haven't been infected with the virus and decide to get vaccinated will have a greater risk of encountering severe symptoms if they actually come down with the disease. He has advised all hospitals to inspect personal medical records before giving out dengue vaccines.
http://www.pattayamail.com/thailandnews/80-dengue-cases-dont-exhibit-symptoms-says-chulalongkorn-uni-199907

[Maps of Thailand: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provinces_of_Thailand and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,151]

Pacific
---
- Samoa. 4 Jan 2018. Dengue fever continues to be a problem in Samoa. In fact, the Director of the Ministry of Health, Leausa Dr Take Naseri, said they have recorded a steady increase in the number of dengue fever cases in the past months, since the 1st case was identified on 27 Oct 2017. "Of all cases diagnosed and reported (clinical and confirmed), males comprised 51 percent (920) of the total, compared to 49 percent (868) of females. "The age group affected is between 1-19 years of age with a national attack rate of 9.3 percent per 1000 people." The majority of the 1788 cases reported to date are from Faleata, Vaimauga, Gagaemauga (Leauva'a), and the Sagaga districts.
http://sobserver.ws/en/05_01_2018/local/28501/Dengue-fever-cases-still-an-issue-Health-warns.htm

- Samoa. 22 Jan 2018. By the end of December 2017, Samoa's health ministry recorded nearly 2500 dengue cases with 5 deaths.
https://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/348593/concerns-in-samoa-as-pacific-s-dengue-challenge-grows

[Maps of Samoa: http://blogs.bard.edu/cepblog/files/2010/08/map_of_samoa.jpg and <Samoa: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,2>]

- American Samoa. 15 Jan 2018. 485 confirmed cases between 1 Nov 2017 and 7 Jan 2018. The areas with the heavy concentration of suspected dengue cases are Ituau, Mauputasi, and Sua.
https://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/348124/call-for-more-action-to-combat-dengue-in-american-samoa

[Maps of American Samoa: http://cdn.tourismontheedge.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/american-samoa-map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5585557,380]

