[2] Philippines: dengue after vaccination
Date: Tue 2 Jan 2018
Source: Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy (CIDRAP) [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/01/three-filipino-children-hospitalized-after-receiving-dengvaxia


According to a story today [2 Jan 2018] in the Manila Times, 3 children recently immunized with Dengvaxia, Sanofi Pasteur's dengue vaccine, are now hospitalized with possible dengue infections.

In related news, a new study shows that receipt of Dengvaxia may affect the accuracy of dengue diagnostic tests [see below].

The hospitalizations come one month after Sanofi recommended Dengvaxia not be used in anyone who is dengue-naive. In recipients without previous dengue infections, the vaccine can lead to more severe illness.

According to Volunteers Against Crime and Corruption (VACC), a non-profit offering free legal assistance to families whose children received Dengvaxia, an 11-, 14-, and 16-year-old were admitted to the Philippine Children's Medical Center on Dec 31 after exhibiting dengue symptoms.

The children received Dengvaxia in the last months of 2017, with the 11-year-old girl completing all 3 shots included of the vaccination. She and the 16-year-old boy, who are from the same village, complained of abdominal discomfort after getting the shots, the Manila Times reported.

The 14-year-old, a boy, received 2 vaccine doses in October [2017].

Dante Jimenez, founding chairman of the VACC, said his group is urging the government to release the names of all children who've received Dengvaxia, but he said the government has not responded to his request.

So far, at least 2 deaths in Filipino children have been linked to Dengvaxia. In both cases, school-aged girls who were dengue-naive developed severe dengue infections shortly after receiving the vaccine.

[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

